Exercise 16.25: Explain the meaning of these declarations:

extern template class vector<string>;
template class vector<Sales_data>;

Answer:
extern template class vector<string> --> template instantiation declaration, extern signals to the compiler
that there will be a nonextern use of this instantiation in a different file.
template class vector<Sales_data>; --> template instantiation declaration, it will instantiate all members
of vector.

Exercise 16.26: Assuming NoDefault is a class that does not have a
default constructor, can we explicitly instantiate vector<NoDefault>? If
not, why not?

Answer:
No, since the declaration will instantiate all members of vector, including members functions
whose default argument is the default constructor of the template parameter type.

Exercise 16.27: For each labeled statement explain what, if any,
instantiations happen. If a template is instantiated, explain why; if not,
explain why not.

template <typename T> class Stack { };
void f1(Stack<char>); // (a)
class Exercise {
Stack<double> &rsd; // (b)
Stack<int> si; // (c)
};
int main() {
Stack<char> *sc; // (d)
f1(*sc); // (e)
int iObj = sizeof(Stack< string >); // (f)

Answer:
a) No instantiation -> f1 is declared but not used so no instantiation occurs.
b) No instantiation -> since rsd is a reference it is not yet constructed.
c) Instantiation of type int will occur since since si is constructed.
d) No instantiation -> since sc is a pointer the Stack object is not constructed.
e) Instantiation -> Direct call to f1 will cause f1 to instantiate.
f) Instantiation -> Direct use of Stack<string> will cause Stack<string> to be instantiated.
